did.abstract: The New York Building Congress (NYBC) is an association representing the construction industry in New York City. Founded in 1921, it now represents 400 organizations totalling over 250,000 skilled workers and professionals. It focuses on supporting sound public policy, promoting productive capital spending, encouraging public/private partnerships, and evaluating the implementation of major government projects in the construction sector. This collection consists of the administrative, general, and event files of the NYBC. It documents the organization's role in establishing standards for construction through the Building Industry Practices Committee, as well as its important role in New York City legislative issues. The event files cover a variety of activities, from the lavishly produced Christmas shows and "Fun and Frolic" celebrations between the 1930s and 1980s, to the more focused luncheons and forums on key issues that became prominent in the 1990s.

custodhist.head: Provenance
custodhist.p: The collection was donated to the Tamiment Library by Richard T. Anderson, President of the New York Building Congress, in 1999. Additional material was donated in 2009 and 2011.

separatedmaterial.head: Separated Materials
separatedmaterial.p: Photographs were separated from the collection and are found in the New York Building Congress Photographs (PHOTOS 109). Periodicals were separated for cataloging by the Library.

relatedmaterial.head: Related Material at the Tamiment Library/Robert F. Wagner Labor Archives
relatedmaterial.p: Building Trades Oral History Project, Audio (OH 45)
The Tamiment Library also holds a substantial number of periodicals published by NYBC, including the Building Congress News, Metrobuild, and Edifice.

bioghist.head: Historical/Biographical Note
bioghist.p: The New York Building Congress (NYBC) is an association representing the construction industry in New York City. Founded in 1921, it now represents 400 organizations totalling over 250,000 skilled workers and professionals. It focuses on supporting sound public policy, promoting productive capital spending, encouraging public/private partnerships, and evaluating the implementation of major government projects in the construction sector.

Shortly after the First World War, elements of the American building industry attempted to organize a national building congress. Although the planned national organization was never very active, the impulse was continued by city-wide groups. In New York City, the 47-member NYBC was organized in early 1921. Originally, membership was limited to organizations (labor unions, businesses, government agencies, etc.), but it was soon opened to individuals.

The broadly based NYBC unites labor and employers, as well as members of multiple professions involved in the building industry. One of its key responsibilities in its early years was to mediate between labor and management.

From its start until the 1960s, the NYBC was heavily involved in setting standards for the building industry. In its first year, the NYBC issued a code of ethics for the building industry. Its later standard-making, particularly in the 1950s and 1960s, was concerned more with specific building practices.

The NYBC has been deeply involved in legislation and regulations relating to the building industry. For example, it took a leading role in the revision of the New York City building code in the 1960s. It has also lobbied on more general issues, such as the New York City charter revision of the late 1980s.

Over the years the organizational structure of the NYBC varied dramatically, as can be seen in the multitude of committees, subcommittees, councils, and boards listed in the inventory below. Nevertheless, certain functions have remained consistent. From the beginning, the NYBC has regularly hosted luncheons that have been addressed by some of New York's, and the nation's, most distinguished individuals.
The NYBC has been led by Richard T. Anderson since 1994. During this time, the NYBC organized the New York Building Foundation (NYBF), which undertakes industry research and philanthropic activities.

scopecontent.head: Scope and Content Note
scopecontent.p: This collection consists of the administrative, general, and event files of the NYBC. It documents the organization's role in establishing standards for construction through the Building Industry Practices Committee, as well as its important role in New York City legislative issues. The event files cover a variety of activities, from the lavishly produced Christmas shows and "Fun and Frolic" celebrations between the 1930s and 1980s, to the more focused luncheons and forums on key issues that became prominent in the 1990s.
Series I: Minutes, 1925-2010 consists of the minutes of the Board of Governors, Board of Directors, Executive Committee, and other NYBC and NYBF committees.

Series II: Administrative Records, 1921-2010 contains memos, reports, and other records relating to the management of the NYBC. Much material is available on the Board of Directors and the Council of Presidents. The many different committees of the NYBC are documented here, especially the Building Industry Practices Committee, the Executive Committee and the Membership Committee. Committee files include agendas, correspondence, and meeting packets. Although none of the records are without gaps, the best coverage is of the 1950s-1990s.
President Richard T. Anderson's chronological file mostly contains his correspondence, but also includes memos, reports, and other documents.

Series III: General Files, 1918-2011 contains correspondence, publications, clippings, and other records. Material is mainly organized into subject files, notably on the New York City building code and charter revisions.

Series IV: Events, 1938-2010 contains the records of the many events organized by the NYBC. The material on the Christmas shows and "Fun and Frolic" shows is particularly rich. There is also substantial material on the 50th Anniversary celebration and the 1995 breakfast forums.
Series V: Oversized Materials, 1947-2008 is comprised of oversized publications, ledgers, and other material.
Series VI: Audio-Visual Materials, 1987-2004 contains VHS videotapes and audio cassettes of various events.

Series VII: Unprocessed Materials, 1985-2011 contains materials related to the Industry Recognition Dinners and Leadership Awards Luncheons, public relations and membership, and the Council of Presidents, as well as photographs and VHS tapes from various events.

arrangement.head: Arrangement
arrangement.p: The collection is arranged into seven series:
Folders in Series I are arranged by organizational hierarchy. Series II-IV are arranged alphabetically. Series VI is arranged by format and then by date. Series VII is unprocessed.
